\]

Still extremely small. Hmm, but considering the density is extremely high, it makes sense that the mean free path is very short. Stars are packed so closely that they would collide almost immediately.

But wait, the problem also gives the average speed of the stars as \(10 \, \text{km/s}\). Does that affect the mean free path? Hmm, actually, the mean free path is independent of the speed of the particles. It only depends on the number density and the cross-sectional area. So, the speed doesn't come into play here.

Therefore, my final answer is approximately \(2 \times 10^{-83}\) cm. But the problem asks for a single significant figure, so I should express it as \(2 \times 10^{-83}\) cm.

Wait, but \(2 \times 10^{-83}\) cm is the same as \(2 \times 10^{-85}\) meters. That's an incredibly small distance, much smaller than the size of an atom. It seems almost impossible for stars to collide under these conditions, but given the high density, it's expected.

So, I think my calculations are correct. The mean free path is indeed on the order of \(10^{-83}\) cm.

