Okay, so I have this problem about iron crystallizing in a body-centered cubic (BCC) unit cell. I need to find the radius of an iron atom. Hmm, let me think about how to approach this.

First, I remember that in a BCC structure, there are atoms at each corner of the cube and one atom in the center. So, each corner atom is shared among eight adjacent cubes, and the center atom is entirely within the cube. That means there are a total of 2 atoms per unit cell.

The density formula for a unit cell is given by:

\[
\text{Density} = \frac{\text{Mass of atoms in unit cell}}{\text{Volume of unit cell}}
\]

I know the density of iron is 7.86 g/cmآ³. So, I can use this formula to find the volume of the unit cell. But to do that, I need the mass of the atoms in the unit cell.

Since iron has an atomic mass of approximately 55.85 g/mol, the mass of two iron atoms (since there are 2 atoms per unit cell) is:

\[
\text{Mass} = 2 \times \frac{55.85 \text{ g/mol}}{6.022 \times 10^{23} \text{ atoms/mol}} = \frac{111.7 \text{ g/mol}}{6.022 \times 10^{23} \text{ atoms/mol}}
\]

Calculating that gives:

\[
\text{Mass} \approx 1.855 \times 10^{-22} \text{ g}
\]

Now, plugging this into the density formula:

\[
7.86 \text{ g/cm}^3 = \frac{1.855 \times 10^{-22} \text{ g}}{\text{Volume of unit cell}}
\]

Solving for the volume:

\[
\text{Volume of unit cell} = \frac{1.855 \times 10^{-22} \text{ g}}{7.86 \text{ g/cm}^3} \approx 2.36 \times 10^{-23} \text{ cm}^3
\]

The volume of a cube is given by \(a^3\), where \(a\) is the edge length of the cube. So,

\[
a^3 = 2.36 \times 10^{-23} \text{ cm}^3
\]

Taking the cube root of both sides:

\[
a = \sqrt[3]{2.36 \times 10^{-23}} \approx 2.87 \times 10^{-8} \text{ cm}
\]

Now, in a BCC structure, the relationship between the edge length \(a\) and the atomic radius \(r\) is given by:

\[
a = 4r / \sqrt{3}
\]

This is because the diagonal of the cube (which is \(a\sqrt{3}\)) is equal to four times the atomic radius. So, solving for \(r\):

\[
r = \frac{a \sqrt{3}}{4}
\]

Plugging in the value of \(a\):

\[
r = \frac{2.87 \times 10^{-8} \text{ cm} \times \sqrt{3}}{4} \approx \frac{2.87 \times 10^{-8} \times 1.732}{4}
\]

Calculating that:

\[
r \approx \frac{4.97 \times 10^{-8}}{4} \approx 1.24 \times 10^{-8} \text{ cm}
\]

So, the radius of an iron atom in this BCC crystal is approximately \(1.24 \times 10^{-8}\) cm.

